\title{yakuba: Access the Drosophila yakuba FlyEM Dataset}
\description{
Provides a thin wrapper around the 'malevnc' package for working with the Drosophila yakuba male VNC neuprint and annotation datasets.
}
\section{Bridging registrations}{
 \code{yakuba} registers a bundled thin-plate
spline transform from \code{yakubaum} to \code{MANC} at package startup when
\code{nat.templatebrains} is available. A simple scaling alias is also added
from \code{yakuba} (nm) to \code{yakubaum} (microns), so
\code{nat.templatebrains::xform_brain()} can chain from \code{yakuba} to \code{MANC}.

Note the current registration (which lives in inst/extdata) was computed by
Sebastian Cachero in April 2025. See \href{https://flyem-cns.slack.com/archives/C07SFDC909W/p1744652271402679?thread_ts=1744645357.564199&cid=C07SFDC909W}{slack for details}
}

\section{Package Options}{

There is currently one package option:

\itemize{
\item \code{yakuba.dataset} keeps track of the active yakuba dataset.
}

You can use this to run your code against the production yakuba dataset or
future snapshot variants. The main ways to do this are:

\enumerate{
\item Use \code{\link[=with_dyak]{with_dyak()}} to run one expression without changing the default
yakuba dataset.
\item Use \code{\link[=choose_dyak_dataset]{choose_dyak_dataset()}} to choose a default yakuba dataset for
the rest of the session.
\item Expert users may set the \code{yakuba.dataset} option directly in their
\code{.Rprofile}.
}
}

